defaultLand Reformdefault&#xa0;
default3.
default              
defaultThe Scottish Countryside Alliance believes that there is a lack
default defaultof clarity over the rationale and 
defaultremit of Land Reform in Scotland
default. The Land Reform (Scotland) Bill Policy Memorandum states that its objective is '
defaultto remove land-based barriers to the sustainable development of rural communities
default' (Scottish Parliament, 2001). However, it is not clear what 
defaultform this sustainable development should take, or what 
defaultthese ‘barriers’ are or what the Bill’s priorities should be
default. For example, some have proposed that the 
defaultBill 
defaultcould focus on reversing local economic and environmental decline, whilst others have suggest
defaulted it could play a role in increasing the population and economic activity of rural communities (
defaultSQW
default, 2007;
default&#xa0;
defaultSQW
default, 2009). 
defaultI
defaultt is not clear whether the '
defaultland based barriers to the sustainable development of rural communities
default' referred to by the Scottish Parlia
defaultment primarily concern land ownership or 
defaultland stewardship,default as both are likely to be important in terms of sustainable development and different measures would be required for each. For example, many of the potential benefits associated with land and asset ownership may not be achievable through community ownershi
defaultp alone, as benefits such as increasing the financial viability of land and improving local services also depend on how these are managed.
default&#xa0;
default3.1
default              
defaultThe Scottish Countryside Alliance (SCA) strongly supports the objective of the sustainable development of rural c
defaultommunities through increasing the opportunities for them to undertake and control the development of their environments. However
default,
default the SCA reject
defaults
default the thought process that barriers to sustainable development will be removed simply by increasing diversity of
default land ownership. Given the agricultural marginality, population scarcity and isolated nature of certain tracts of the countryside, parts of it simply cannot be economically sustainable without sources of external funding.   
default&#xa0;
default3.
default2
default              
defaultThe community/tenant absol
defaultute right to buy dominates the academic literature in comparison to either access rights or the crofting community right to buy. Arguably that perception remains despite the fact that it has had little direct use in purchasing land or other assets for comm
defaultunity/tenant ownership. Aside from the challenges thrown up by the administrative processes of the community right to buy and the need to manage potential conflict with landowners’ interests, much depends on the human and financial resources available to a
default group with regards to whether they will engage with the Act. It remains the case that most community groups’ experience of the Act has been confined to going through attempted or actual registration of an interest to purchase land, with no actual gain of 
defaultland or assets.
