default3.4
default              
defaultMany of the observations made in relation to the community right to buy are equally applicable to the crofting 
defaultcommunity right to buy. Indeed, the challenges associated with the definition of the crofting community, mapping of the land to be purchased and balloting of the community make it an even more daunting process to embark upon than that of the community righ
defaultt to buy. 
default&#xa0;
default3.5
default              
defaultThe Crofting and Community right to buy 
defaultopportunity has
default struggled to inspire communities to take up ownership for a number of reasons, but fundamentally, prospective applicants are failing through the lack of a financially viable business plan as opposed to an unresponsive or hostile landowner
default. 
defaultResearch highli
defaultghts that not all communities are equally well placed to achieve the full benefits of land and asset ownership. In addition, without the right conditions in place, ownership can bring with it more risks than benefits.  (Aiken et al, 2011; JRF, 2011; Skerra
defaulttt, 2011).
default&#xa0;
default3.6
default              
defaultThe Scottish Countryside Alliance (SCA) welcomes the principle of developing further the ability for more people in rural and urban Scotland to have a stake in the ownership, governance, management and use of land, which will lead to a 
defaultgreater diversity of land ownership, and ownership types in Scotland. However we may have a differ
defaultent understanding of 
defaultwhat constitutes success in relation to Land Reform in Scotland.
default&#xa0;
default3.7
default              
defaultWe believe that landowners and private estates in Scotland are some
defaulttimes unfairly portrayed as being separate from their local communities and cited for holding back or prohibiting development. This is an inaccurate generalisation. 
defaultLandowners in Scotland are not the standardised stereotype some portray, but come in all sh
defaultapes and sizes; individuals, trusts and communities. Whatever the ownership type they are all engaged in diverse economic activity delivering sustainable economic growth throughout Scotland; which is far more important to Scotland’s communities and economy
default, than simply asking “who owns the land”. 
default&#xa0;
