default4.6
default              
defaultWhile there are aspects of Land Value Tax in its purest sense which might be worthy of further detailed consideration in the context of reform of the taxation of land and property, we have concerns that what has been proposed as “Land Value Taxation” by ce
defaultrtain analysts in relation to possible Land Reform in Scotland falls well short of the principles of Land Value Tax explained in some detail in the Mirrlees Review. In that 
defaultr
defaulteview, it is suggested that Land Value Tax would replace a number of other taxes (
defaultincluding taxation of rental property, Council Tax, Business Rates and Stamp Duty Land Tax). With 
defaultonly 
defaultpart of the taxation system currently devolved (a proportion of Income Tax, Business Rates, Council
default Tax and, from 2015, Land and Buildings Transaction Tax and Landfill Tax), it is not possible 
defaultat this time 
defaultto consider the introduction of a pure form of Land Value Tax in Scotland.
default&#xa0;
default4.7
default              
defaultThe SCA does not believe that there is a need to change t
defaulthe law of su
defaultccession governing how a person's property passes on after his or her death. It is our understanding that in Scotland the distribution of a person's testate or partially intestate estate is governed by the Succession (Scotland) Act 1964 - the Act provides 
defaultfor the estate to be distributed in a specific way and according to law to the surviving relatives of the deceased.  
defaultIt is our understanding that the most recent review of succession by the Law Commission Scotland focussed more on how people lived in Scotl
defaultand in relation to their marital or civil relationship status as opposed to where they live and what they bequeathed after death. Further to this, significant evidence was submitted to the Law Commission review in relation to the detrimental effects of “la
defaultnd fragmentation” where families had differing levels of claim to landed or agricultural holding. 
